{"title_page": "Corticopontine fibers", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2008}}\n{{Infobox brain\n| Name            = Corticopontine fibers\n| Latin           = fibrae corticopontinae, tractus corticopontinus\n| Image           = Gray710.png\n| Caption         = Coronal section through [[mid-brain]].  <br>1. [[Corpora quadrigemina]]. <br>2. [[Cerebral aqueduct]]. <br>3. [[Central gray stratum]]. <br>4. [[Interpeduncular space]]. <br>5. [[Sulcus lateralis]]. <br>6. [[Substantia nigra]]. <br>7. [[Red nucleus]] of [[tegmentum]]. <br>8. [[Oculomotor nerve]], with 8\u2019, its nucleus of origin. a. [[Lemniscus (anatomy)|Lemniscus]] (in blue) with a\u2019 the [[medial lemniscus]] and a\" the [[lateral lemniscus]]. b. [[Medial longitudinal fasciculus]]. c. [[Raphe|Raph\u00e9]]. d. Temporopontine fibers. e. Portion of [[medial lemniscus]], which runs to the [[lentiform nucleus]] and [[Insular cortex|insula]]. f. [[Cerebrospinal fibers]]. g. [[Frontopontine fibers]].\n| Image2          =\n| Caption2        =\n| System          =\n| Artery          =\n| Vein            =\n}}\n'''Corticopontine fibers'''<ref>{{cite journal | author = Kamali A, Kramer LA, Frye RE, Butler IJ, Hasan KM | date = Oct 2010 | title = Diffusion tensor tractography of the human brain cortico-ponto-cerebellar pathways: a quantitative preliminary study | journal = J Magn Reson Imaging | volume = 32 | issue = 4| pages = 809\u201317 | doi = 10.1002/jmri.22330 | pmid = 20882611 | pmc = 4492525 }}</ref> are projections from the [[cerebral cortex]] to the [[pontine nuclei]].<ref name=\"pmid18982130\">{{cite journal |author=Leergaard TB, Bjaalie JG |title=Topography of the complete corticopontine projection: From experiments to principal Maps |journal=Front Neurosci |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=211\u201323 |date=November 2007 |pmid=18982130 |pmc=2518056 |doi=10.3389/neuro.01.1.1.016.2007 }}</ref>\n\nDepending upon the lobe of origin, they can be classified as [[frontopontine fibers]], [[parietopontine fibers]], [[temporopontine fibers]] or [[occipitopontine fibers]].<ref>http://braininfo.rprc.washington.edu/AncilDefinition.aspx?ID=1322&questID=1322{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\nCortex->Pons->Cerebellum: \n* https://www.csuchico.edu/~pmccaffrey/syllabi/CMSD%20320/362unit7.html\n* {{BrainstemWisconsin|16Pontine}}\n\n{{Pons}}\n{{Mesencephalon}}\n{{Neural tracts}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cerebral white matter]]\n\n\n{{neuroanatomy-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2008}}\n{{Infobox brain\n| Name            = Corticopontine fibers\n| Latin           = fibrae corticopontinae, tractus corticopontinus\n| Image           = Gray710.png\n| Caption         = Coronal section through [[mid-brain]].  <br>1. [[Corpora quadrigemina]]. <br>2. [[Cerebral aqueduct]]. <br>3. [[Central gray stratum]]. <br>4. [[Interpeduncular space]]. <br>5. [[Sulcus lateralis]]. <br>6. [[Substantia nigra]]. <br>7. [[Red nucleus]] of [[tegmentum]]. <br>8. [[Oculomotor nerve]], with 8\u2019, its nucleus of origin. a. [[Lemniscus (anatomy)|Lemniscus]] (in blue) with a\u2019 the [[medial lemniscus]] and a\" the [[lateral lemniscus]]. b. [[Medial longitudinal fasciculus]]. c. [[Raphe|Raph\u00e9]]. d. Temporopontine fibers. e. Portion of [[medial lemniscus]], which runs to the [[lentiform nucleus]] and [[Insular cortex|insula]]. f. [[Cerebrospinal fibers]]. g. [[Frontopontine fibers]].\n| Image2          =\n| Caption2        =\n| System          =\n| Artery          =\n| Vein            =\n}}\n'''Corticopontine fibers'''<ref>Kamali A, Kramer LA, Frye RE, Butler IJ, Hasan KM. Diffusion tensor tractography of the human brain cortico-ponto-cerebellar pathways: a quantitative preliminary study. J Magn Reson Imaging. 2010 Oct;32(4):809-17. doi: 10.1002/jmri.22330. {{PMID|20882611}}\n\n</ref> are projections from the [[cerebral cortex]] to the [[pontine nuclei]].<ref name=\"pmid18982130\">{{cite journal |author=Leergaard TB, Bjaalie JG |title=Topography of the complete corticopontine projection: From experiments to principal Maps |journal=Front Neurosci |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=211\u201323 |date=November 2007 |pmid=18982130 |pmc=2518056 |doi=10.3389/neuro.01.1.1.016.2007 }}</ref>\n\nDepending upon the lobe of origin, they can be classified as [[frontopontine fibers]], [[parietopontine fibers]], [[temporopontine fibers]] or [[occipitopontine fibers]].<ref>http://braininfo.rprc.washington.edu/AncilDefinition.aspx?ID=1322&questID=1322{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\nCortex->Pons->Cerebellum: \n* https://www.csuchico.edu/~pmccaffrey/syllabi/CMSD%20320/362unit7.html\n* {{BrainstemWisconsin|16Pontine}}\n\n{{Pons}}\n{{Mesencephalon}}\n{{Neural tracts}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cerebral white matter]]\n\n\n{{neuroanatomy-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corticopontine_fibers"}
{"title_page": "Diaspora Yeshiva Band", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Diaspora Yeshiva Band\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[Jerusalem]]\n| genre            = [[Jewish rock]], [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]], [[Country music|country]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[blues]], [[jazz]], [[klezmer]]\n| years_active     = {{start date|1975}}\u2013{{end date|1983}}\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora\n| website          = {{URL|www.diasporaband.com}}<br>{{URL| http://rockinrabbi.com/bio.php}}\n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = {{hlist||Avraham Rosenblum|Simcha Abramson|Ruby Harris|Menachem Herman|Gedaliah Goldstein|Amram Hakohen |Beryl Glaser| Todros Glaser|[[Ben Zion Solomon]]|[[Adam Wexler]]|Yochanan Lederman|Shimon Green}}\n}}\n\n'''Diaspora Yeshiva Band''' ({{lang-he|\u05dc\u05d4\u05e7\u05ea \u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05ea\u05e4\u05d5\u05e6\u05d5\u05ea}}) was an Israeli [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] [[Jewish rock]] band founded at the Diaspora Yeshiva on [[Mount Zion]], [[Jerusalem]], by ''[[baal teshuva]]'' students from the United States. In existence from 1975 to 1983, the band infused [[Rock music|rock]] and [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] music with Jewish lyrics, creating a style of music it called \"Hasidic rock\"{{sfn|Tilbury|1989|p=193}} or \"Country and Eastern\".<ref name=bio>{{cite web |url= http://www.diasporaband.com/biography/|title=Biography|publisher=Diaspora Yeshiva Band|year=2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=forward>{{cite web |url= http://forward.com/articles/13320/a-jewish-pop-band-worth-the-wait-/|title=A Jewish Pop Band Worth the Wait|first=Alexander|last=Gelfand|date=8 May 2008|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[The Forward]]}}</ref> The band was very popular on college campuses in the early to mid-1980s, and was well known in Jerusalem for its Saturday-night concerts at [[David's Tomb]]. It had a considerable influence on [[contemporary Jewish religious music]], inspiring later bands such as [[Blue Fringe]], [[8th Day (Jewish band)|8th Day]], [[Reva L'Sheva]], [[Soulfarm]], the [[Moshav (band)|Moshav Band]], and [[Shlock Rock]]. Fifteen years after it disbanded, band leader Avraham Rosenblum revived the band under the name '''Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora''' and produced several more albums.\n\n== Background ==\nThe '''Diaspora Yeshiva''' <ref>[https://diasporayeshiva.weebly.com/ Website of the Diaspora Yeshiva]</ref> was founded in 1967 by Rabbi Mordechai Goldstein, an alumnus of the [[Yeshivas Chofetz Chaim|Chofetz Chaim Yeshiva]] in [[Queens]], New York, and a colleague of Rabbi [[Shlomo Carlebach (musician)|Shlomo Carlebach]].{{sfn|Lange|Diethard Romheld|Weigol|2011|p=330}}  It is the only Jewish institution located on [[Mount Zion]]. The yeshiva offers programs ranging from basic Judaism to advanced Talmud - employing a methodology based on [[Moshe_Chaim_Luzzatto#Bibliography|Ramchal]] - and emphasizes ''[[mussar]]'' (character development);\nsee [[Yeshiva #Curriculum]].\n'''Machon Roni''', a [[Midrasha|Women's Torah Seminary]], operates in parallel.\n\nDiaspora Yeshiva was the first [[Orthodox Jewish outreach|outreach]] [[yeshiva]] for [[Baal teshuva movement|''baalei teshuva'']].{{sfn|Lange|Diethard Romheld|Weigol|2011|p=330}}{{sfn|Kaplan|2013|p=291}} Unlike traditional rabbinic academies, the yeshiva reached out to young Jewish men who had never been exposed to traditional [[Torah study|Torah]] or [[Talmud]] study. It offered introductory and intermediate courses together with acclimation to an Orthodox Jewish lifestyle.{{sfn|Lange|Diethard Romheld|Weigol|2011|p=330}} To appeal to students who identified with the [[hippie]] [[subculture]] prevalent on American college campuses in those years, the yeshiva adopted a [[Neo-Hasidism|neo-Hasidic]] approach. Students were encouraged to keep their long hair and their musical instruments.{{sfn|Lange|Diethard Romheld|Weigol|2011|p=331}}\n\nNumerous students were professional or semi-professional musicians, and several musical collaborations were spawned in the yeshiva dorms.<ref name=mish/> In 1975 student Avraham Rosenblum, a rock guitarist who had started his own band in New York in 1970, founded the Diaspora Yeshiva Band.<ref name=mish/>{{sfn|Strom|2011|p=196}} The band became an outreach tool for other hippie students and, later, post-hippie seekers, using [[Jewish music]] to draw them into the milieu of [[Torah study]].{{sfn|Lange|Diethard Romheld|Weigol|2011|p=331}}<ref name=mish/>\n\n==History==\nThe Diaspora Yeshiva Band staged its first concert at the [[Gerard Behar Center|Beit Ha'Am]] hall in the [[Nachlaot]] neighborhood of Jerusalem during [[Hanukkah]] 1975.<ref name=mish/> After that, the band became well known for its weekly Saturday-night concerts held in a room adjacent to [[David's Tomb]] (located in the same courtyard as the yeshiva) on Mount Zion.<ref name=mish/>{{sfn|Selavan|1993|p=88}}{{sfn|Sofer|1995|p=92}} These concerts attracted American, British and French secular youth; yeshiva and seminary students; and Israeli soldiers.<ref name=mish/> Band members continued to perform with the group even after they had married and begun studying in [[kollel]].<ref name=mish/>\n\nThe band released its first album in 1976.{{sfn|Strom|2011|p=196}}<ref name=beatles/> In 1977 it was invited to compete in the Hasidic Song Festival, an Israeli contest that ran from 1969 to 1984 and that was broadcast on national television.<ref name=mish/> Diaspora was the first yeshiva band to perform in the largely secular music event, and won first prize for its song \"''Hu Yiftach Libeinu''\" (He will open our hearts).<ref name=mish/> Interviews in the general media followed, increasing name recognition and visitors to the Saturday-night concerts.<ref name=mish/> The band was invited back for the 1978 Hasidic Song Festival, and won first prize for its song \"''Malchutcha''\" (Your sovereignty).<ref name=mish/>\n\nThe band embarked on its first North American concert tour in 1979, visiting 26 cities.<ref name=mish/> It went on to tour the U.S., Canada, Europe, and South Africa on five additional tours.<ref name=beatles/><ref name=shapiro>{{cite web |url=http://jewishtimes.com/17785/diaspora-yeshiva-band-reunites-after-almost-two-decades/#.U8W-W_mSzkU|last=Shapiro|first=Marc|title=Diaspora Yeshiva Band Reunites After Almost Two Decades|work=[[Baltimore Jewish Times]]|date=16 January 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> The band was highly popular on college campuses in the early to mid-1980s.{{sfn|Strom|2011|p=196}}<ref name=nymag>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GegCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA116&dq=diaspora+band |title=Music & Dance|journal=[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]|volume=15|issue=1|date=28 December 1981|accessdate=16 November 2014|page=116}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, [[Lynyrd Skynyrd]] drummer [[Artimus Pyle]] came to study in the Diaspora Yeshiva for several years.<ref name=arutz/> He played with the band and bequeathed his drum set to the yeshiva.<ref name=arutz>{{cite web |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/181355#.VFLBH_mUeHg|title=The Lynyrd Skynyrd Connection to Mount Zion & King David's Tomb|first=Ben|last=Bresky|work=[[Arutz Sheva|Israel National News]]|date=3 June 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=harris/> In 1987 the Diaspora Yeshiva Band performed and was interviewed on [[MTV]]'s Musical Passport series, ''Rock Israel'', as part of the coverage of the visit of [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers]] to Israel and Egypt.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?id=131506273571990&story_fbid=728705840518694|title=Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers Rock Israel 1987 (video)|publisher=Diaspora Yeshiva Band |accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=exponent/> Band leader Avraham Rosenblum was filmed accompanying [[Tom Petty]], [[Benmont Tench]], and [[Roger McGuinn]] at the [[Western Wall]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gruntig.net/2012/07/avraham-rosenblum-with-non-jewish-rock.html |title= Avraham Rosenblum with non-Jewish rock stars (video)|date=25 July 2012|accessdate=16 November 2014|publisher=gruntig.net}}</ref>\n\nThe Diaspora Yeshiva Band released a total of six albums.<ref name=mish/><ref name=sun/> It disbanded in 1983<ref name=bio/><ref name=sun/> as its members began pursuing both solo careers and careers in Torah learning and [[Orthodox Jewish outreach|outreach]].<ref name=mish/>\n\n===Reunions===\nIn December 1992 the band reconvened for a month-long<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/diasporayeshivaband|title=Live at Carnegie Hall &ndash; The Reunion|publisher=Sameach Music|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> reunion tour beginning with a performance at [[Carnegie Hall]].<ref name=beatles/><ref name=back>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-107976992.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042710/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-107976992.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 March 2015|title=Back From Musical Diaspora|first=George|last=Robinson|work=[[The Jewish Week]]|date=11 March 2005|accessdate=16 November 2014}} {{subscription}}</ref> It reunited again in 1996 with a show at [[The Town Hall (New York City)|The Town Hall]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=exponent>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2379407.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042701/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2379407.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 March 2015 |title= It's the Rockin' Rabbi: Avraham Rosenblum attuned to power of true music|first=Michael|last=Elkin|work=[[The Jewish Exponent]]|date=15 December 1995|accessdate=16 November 2014}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Rosenblum, Simcha Abramson, Gedaliah Goldstein, Ruby Harris, and Menachem Herman performed at the [[Hebrew Academy for Special Children#A Time for Music|HASC]] 27 concert at Lincoln Center.<ref name=mish>Besser, Yisroel. \"We All Get Another Chance\". ''[[Mishpacha]]'', March 12, 2014, pp. 48-58.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltimorejewishlife.com/news/news-detail.php?SECTION_ID=1&ARTICLE_ID=45577|title=HASC Donor Pays $300,000 for an Avraham Rosenblum Song|date=16 January 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=Baltimore Jewish Life|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129021253/http://baltimorejewishlife.com/news/news-detail.php?SECTION_ID=1&ARTICLE_ID=45577|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> That same year, the group held another reunion concert at [[Congregation Shomrei Emunah]] in Baltimore, where Rosenblum is a member.<ref name=shapiro/>\n\n===Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora===\nIn 1998 band leader Avraham Rosenblum and his son, drummer Moe Rosenblum, revived the band under the name '''Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora''' and produced the album ''Jerusalem is Calling''.<ref name=back/><ref name=av>{{cite web |url=http://rockinrabbi.com/bio.php|title=Biography/Information|publisher=Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora|year=2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-94584732.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042714/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-94584732.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= 29 March 2015|title=Like Father, Like Son|first=Steve|last=Lipman|date=26 March 2004|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=The Jewish Week}} {{subscription}}</ref> The pair went on to produce ''The Diaspora Collection'' (2000), a digitally-remastered double-CD of Diaspora Yeshiva Band hits, and ''Kedem'' (2003), an album featuring solo material by Avraham Rosenblum.<ref name=back/><ref name=av/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-93680585.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042716/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-93680585.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 March 2015|title=Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora: Kedem|first=Ben|last=Jacobson|date=21 April 2004|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=The Jerusalem Post}} {{subscription}}></ref>\n\n==Music style==\n{{Quote box\n |width=300px\n |align=right\n |quoted=true\n |bgcolor=#c6dbf7 \n |salign=right\n |quote=\"They started putting their music talents together in a religious way ... You remember that song \"[[Joy to the World (Three Dog Night song)|Jeremiah Was a Bullfrog]]\"? Well, it was the same sound, but they were singing about how wonderful God is\". |source=Shelley Lang, promoter<ref name=sun/>\n}}\nThe band members viewed their music as a means of expressing their newfound connection to God, the Jewish people, and the Land of Israel in a medium that they were familiar with.<ref name=bio/><ref name=report>{{cite web |url=http://jewishmusicreport.com/2009/11/17/ethnomusicology-the-americanization-of-niggunim/|title=Ethnomusicology &ndash; The Americanization of Niggunim|date=17 November 2009|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=Jewish Music Report}}</ref> Their arrangements reflected the musical trends of secular American culture in the late 1960s and early 1970s.<ref name=mish/> The band's repertoire included [[Rock music|rock]], [[soft rock]], [[acid rock]], [[Country music|country]], [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]], [[blues]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[jazz]], [[klezmer]], and [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]] ballads.<ref name=beatles>{{cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-12-18/features/9204250297_1_king-david-rock-diaspora-yeshiva-band |title='Jewish Beatles'|first=Anthony |last=DeBartolo|date=18 December 1992|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref><ref name=nymag/>{{sfn|Ledgin|2004|p=52}}<ref>Cohen, Judah M. (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZnbXkSNJa1gC&pg=PA107 \"Exploring the Postmodern Landscape of Jewish Music\u201d], in '' 'You Should See Yourself': Jewish Identity in Postmodern American Culture\", Vincent Brock, ed. Rutgers University Press, {{ISBN|081353996X}}, p. 107.</ref>{{sfn|Heilman|1986|pp=183-184}} [[Yale Strom|Strom]] describes their music as blending \"a San Francisco rock 'n' roll sound with Israeli, Middle Eastern, and Hasidic music\".{{sfn|Strom|2011|p=196}}\n\nInstrumentation included [[electric guitar]], [[rhythm guitar]], [[bass guitar]], [[saxophone]], [[fiddle]], [[banjo]], and [[Drum kit|drums]].<ref name=mish/><ref name=sun/> The band was noted for its guitar harmonies<ref name=shapiro/> and \"virtuoso\" instrument playing.<ref name=shapiro/><ref name=klig/>\n\nThe lyrics, in contrast, expressed Jewish values. Lyrics were both original and drawn from the [[Torah]] and [[Book of Psalms]].<ref name=beatles/><ref name=sun>{{cite web |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1992-12-26/news/9203080643_1_band-members-rock-band-reunion-tour|title=Jewish Band Takes Rock To Higher Level|first=Kirstin Norling|last=Walker|date=26 December 1992|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]}}</ref> The band sang in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]], and [[English language|English]].{{sfn|Tilbury|1989|p=193}} Their on-stage presence also belied the traditional rock band image: they sported full beards, ''[[payot]]'', and ''[[tzitzit]]'',{{sfn|Heilman|1986|pp=183-184}} and dressed in the dark-colored attire typical of yeshiva students.<ref name=bio/><ref name=mish/>\n\n==Influence==\nThe Diaspora Yeshiva Band was considered an influential group in the history of contemporary Jewish religious music.<ref name=klig>{{cite journal |url=http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=14722 |title=Contemporary Jewish Music in America|first=Mark|last=Kligman|year=2001|journal=American Jewish Yearbook|publisher=[[American Jewish Committee]]|page=109}}</ref> Bands that name them as an inspiration include [[Blue Fringe]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-87056408.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042706/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-87056408.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 March 2015|title=New Jewish Band Makes Waves|first=Michael|last=Freund|date=11 November 2003|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=The Jerusalem Post}} {{subscription}}</ref> [[8th Day (Jewish band)|8th Day]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kessertorah.nsw.edu.au/events/8thday.html|title=About 8th Day|publisher=Kesser Torah College|year=2012|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> and [[Shlock Rock]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.jta.org/2012/01/25/arts-entertainment/25-years-later-shlock-rock-is-still-rockin|title=25 years later, Shlock Rock is still rockin'|first=Michael|last=Feldstein|date=25 January 2012|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency|JTA]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-92661010.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042704/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-92661010.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= 29 March 2015|title=Solomon Keeps On Schlockin'|first=Ben|last=Jacobson|date=25 March 2004|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=The Jerusalem Post}} {{subscription}}</ref> Besides Rosenblum, other original band members who pursued solo careers include Ruby Harris, founder of the Ruby Harris Electric Violin Blues Band in Chicago,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.juf.org/interactive/default.aspx?id=75039 |title= AUDIO: Paul Wieder interviews Ruby Harris |date=3 February 2009|accessdate=16 November 2014|publisher=[[Jewish United Fund]]}}</ref> [[Adam Wexler]], co-founder of [[Reva L'Sheva]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.jpost.com/Arts-and-Culture/Music/Reva-LShevas-seven-year-itch-336804|title=Reva L'Sheva's seven-year itch|first=David|last=Brinn|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=1 January 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> and Rabbi Moshe Shur, founder of the Moshe Shur Band and Moshe Shur and Sons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qchron.com/editions/north/rabbi-moshe-shur-a-renaissance-man/article_f2b55433-69ac-55de-9d60-8dee638f1fb8.html|title=Rabbi Moshe Shur: A renaissance man|first=Jason|last=Cohen|date=3 March 2011|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[Queens Chronicle]]}}</ref> Sons of original band member [[Ben Zion Solomon]] include [[Noah Solomon]] of [[Soulfarm]], [[Yehuda Solomon]] of [[Moshav (band)|Moshav Band]], and Nachman Solomon of [[Hamakor (band)|Hamakor]].<ref name=forward/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117460491.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042708/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117460491.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= 29 March 2015|title=Two Start-Up Bands Step Up|first=Ben |last=Jacobson|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=13 January 2006|accessdate=16 November 2014}} {{subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/music/article/the_source_of_haumlmakor_its_all_in_the_family_20080625 |title= The source of h\u00e4MAKOR &ndash; It's all in the family|first=Paula|last=Roth|date=26 June 2008|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nThe six founding members of the Diaspora Yeshiva Band were:<ref name=mish/><ref name=harris>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishmag.com/114mag/band/band.htm|title=The Band That Changed Jewish Music|first=Ruby|last=Harris|date=June 2007|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=The Jewish Magazine}}</ref> \n* Avraham Rosenblum \u2013 guitar\n* [[Ben Zion Solomon]] \u2013 fiddle, banjo\n* Simcha Abramson \u2013 saxophone, clarinet\n* Ruby Harris \u2013 violin, mandolin, guitar, harmonica\n* [[Adam Wexler]] \u2013 bass\n* Gedalia Goldstein \u2013 drums\n\nStudent-musicians who played with the band at different times between 1973 and 1986 include: Beryl and Ted Glaser, Shimon Green, Isser Blum, Amram Hakohen, Menachem Herman, Yochanan Lederman, Tzvi Miller, Yosil Rosenzweig, [[Chaim-Dovid Saracik]], and Rabbi Moshe Shur.<ref name=harris/>\n\n==Discography==\n===Diaspora Yeshiva Band===\n* ''The Diaspora Yeshiva Band'' (1976)\n* ''Melave Malka with the Diaspora Yeshiva Band'' (1977)\n* ''At the Gate of Return'' (1978)\n* ''Live From King David's Tomb'' (1980)\n* ''Land of Our Fathers'' (1981)\n* ''Diaspora Live on Mt. Zion'' (1982)\n* ''Live at Carnegie Hall'' (1992)\n* ''The Diaspora Collection'' (2000)\n\n===Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora===\n* ''Jerusalem is Calling'' (1998)\n* ''Kedem'' (2003)\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=AZttAAAAMAAJ&q=diaspora+yeshiva+band|title=A Walker in Jerusalem|first=Samuel C.|last=Heilman|authorlink=Samuel Heilman|publisher=Summit Books|year=1986|isbn= 0671544330}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0NrIPT7KWTYC&pg=PT325 |title=Contemporary American Judaism: Transformation and renewal|first=Dana Evan|last=Kaplan|year=2013|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=0231510411}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZbDQpgZILuwC&pg=PA330 |title=Judaism and Crisis: Crisis as a catalyst in Jewish cultural history|first1=Armin |last1=Lange|first2=K. F. |last2=Diethard Romheld|first3=Matthias|last3=Weigol|year=2011|publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht|isbn=3525542089}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7kgBY8tV6zYC&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52|title=Homegrown Music: Discovering Bluegrass|last=Ledgin|first=Stephanie P. |year=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=0275981150}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kAxLAn6sOb4C&pg=PA129 |title= Popular Music and National Culture in Israel|first1= Motti |last1=Regev|first2=Edwin|last2=Seroussi|year=2004|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=0520236548}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url= https://books.google.com/books?ei=7mFNVIK-M4TPaM2ugYgC&id=eJJtAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=band+concert |last=Selavan|first=Barnea Levi|title=Tzaddik's Guide to Jerusalem's Old City|year=1993|publisher=B. L. Selavan}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fxgZfheWUrIC&pg=PA92|title=Kids Love Israel \u2013 Israel Loves Kids: A travel guide for families|first=Barbara|last=Sofer|year=1995|publisher=Kar-Ben Publishing|isbn=0929371895}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i7w0s2ddCMEC&pg=PA196 |title=The Book of Klezmer: The history, the music, the folklore|first=Yale|last=Strom|authorlink=Yale Strom|year=2011|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=1613740638|edition=Reprint}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LSO7AAAAIAAJ&q=diaspora+yeshiva+band|title=Israel, a travel survival kit|first=Neil|last=Tilbury|year=1989|publisher=[[Lonely Planet]]|isbn= 0864420153}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.diasporaband.com/video/ Diaspora Band Video Channel]\n*[http://www.jewishpress.com/tv/video-picks/the-diaspora-yeshiva-band-1979/2014/04/25/ \"The Diaspora Yeshiva Band (1979)\"] (video)\n*[http://www.israelnationalnews.com/Radio/News.aspx/3206#.VF_oNPmUewR \u201cAudio: Avraham Rosenblum - Diaspora Yeshiva Band & Beyond\u201d] 2011 live performance and interview\n\n{{Contemporary Jewish religious music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diaspora Yeshiva Band}}\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Israeli rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1975]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:Jewish rock groups]]\n[[Category:Jewish folk rock groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Diaspora Yeshiva Band\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[Jerusalem]]\n| genre            = [[Jewish rock]], [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]], [[Country music|country]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[blues]], [[jazz]], [[klezmer]]\n| years_active     = {{start date|1975}}\u2013{{end date|1983}}\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora\n| website          = {{URL|www.diasporaband.com}}<br>{{URL| http://rockinrabbi.com/bio.php}}\n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = {{hlist||Avraham Rosenblum|Simcha Abramson|Ruby Harris|Menachem Herman|Gedaliah Goldstein|Amram Hakohen |Beryl Glaser| Todros Glaser|[[Ben Zion Solomon]]|[[Adam Wexler]]|Yochanan Lederman|Shimon Green}}\n}}\n\n'''Diaspora Yeshiva Band''' ({{lang-he|\u05dc\u05d4\u05e7\u05ea \u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05ea\u05e4\u05d5\u05e6\u05d5\u05ea}}) was an Israeli [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] [[Jewish rock]] band founded at the Diaspora Yeshiva on [[Mount Zion]], [[Jerusalem]], by ''[[baal teshuva]]'' students from the United States. In existence from 1975 to 1983, the band infused [[Rock music|rock]] and [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] music with Jewish lyrics, creating a style of music it called \"Hasidic rock\"{{sfn|Tilbury|1989|p=193}} or \"Country and Eastern\".<ref name=bio>{{cite web |url= http://www.diasporaband.com/biography/|title=Biography|publisher=Diaspora Yeshiva Band|year=2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=forward>{{cite web |url= http://forward.com/articles/13320/a-jewish-pop-band-worth-the-wait-/|title=A Jewish Pop Band Worth the Wait|first=Alexander|last=Gelfand|date=8 May 2008|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[The Forward]]}}</ref> The band was very popular on college campuses in the early to mid-1980s, and was well known in Jerusalem for its Saturday-night concerts at [[David's Tomb]]. It had a considerable influence on [[contemporary Jewish religious music]], inspiring later bands such as [[Blue Fringe]], [[8th Day (Jewish band)|8th Day]], [[Reva L'Sheva]], [[Soulfarm]], the [[Moshav (band)|Moshav Band]], and [[Shlock Rock]]. Fifteen years after it disbanded, band leader Avraham Rosenblum revived the band under the name '''Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora''' and produced several more albums.\n\n== Background ==\nThe '''Diaspora Yeshiva''' <ref>[https://diasporayeshiva.weebly.com/ Website of the Diaspora Yeshiva]</ref> was founded in 1967 by Rabbi Mordechai Goldstein, an alumnus of the [[Yeshivas Chofetz Chaim|Chofetz Chaim Yeshiva]] in [[Queens]], New York, and a colleague of Rabbi [[Shlomo Carlebach (musician)|Shlomo Carlebach]].{{sfn|Lange|Diethard Romheld|Weigol|2011|p=330}}  It is the only Jewish institution located on [[Mount Zion]]. The yeshiva offers programs ranging from basic Judaism to advanced Talmud - employing a methodology based on [[Moshe_Chaim_Luzzatto#Bibliography|Ramchal]] - and emphasizes ''[[mussar]]'' (character development);\nsee [[Yeshiva #Curriculum]].\n'''Machon Roni''', a [[Midrasha|Women's Torah Seminary]] operates in parallel.\n\nDiaspora Yeshiva was the first [[Orthodox Jewish outreach|outreach]] [[yeshiva]] for [[Baal teshuva movement|''baalei teshuva'']].{{sfn|Lange|Diethard Romheld|Weigol|2011|p=330}}{{sfn|Kaplan|2013|p=291}} Unlike traditional rabbinic academies, the yeshiva reached out to young Jewish men who had never been exposed to traditional [[Torah study|Torah]] or [[Talmud]] study. It offered introductory and intermediate courses together with acclimation to an Orthodox Jewish lifestyle.{{sfn|Lange|Diethard Romheld|Weigol|2011|p=330}} To appeal to students who identified with the [[hippie]] [[subculture]] prevalent on American college campuses in those years, the yeshiva adopted a [[Neo-Hasidism|neo-Hasidic]] approach. Students were encouraged to keep their long hair and their musical instruments.{{sfn|Lange|Diethard Romheld|Weigol|2011|p=331}}\n\nNumerous students were professional or semi-professional musicians, and several musical collaborations were spawned in the yeshiva dorms.<ref name=mish/> In 1975 student Avraham Rosenblum, a rock guitarist who had started his own band in New York in 1970, founded the Diaspora Yeshiva Band.<ref name=mish/>{{sfn|Strom|2011|p=196}} The band became an outreach tool for other hippie students and, later, post-hippie seekers, using [[Jewish music]] to draw them into the milieu of [[Torah study]].{{sfn|Lange|Diethard Romheld|Weigol|2011|p=331}}<ref name=mish/>\n\n==History==\nThe Diaspora Yeshiva Band staged its first concert at the [[Gerard Behar Center|Beit Ha'Am]] hall in the [[Nachlaot]] neighborhood of Jerusalem during [[Hanukkah]] 1975.<ref name=mish/> After that, the band became well known for its weekly Saturday-night concerts held in a room adjacent to [[David's Tomb]] (located in the same courtyard as the yeshiva) on Mount Zion.<ref name=mish/>{{sfn|Selavan|1993|p=88}}{{sfn|Sofer|1995|p=92}} These concerts attracted American, British and French secular youth; yeshiva and seminary students; and Israeli soldiers.<ref name=mish/> Band members continued to perform with the group even after they had married and begun studying in [[kollel]].<ref name=mish/>\n\nThe band released its first album in 1976.{{sfn|Strom|2011|p=196}}<ref name=beatles/> In 1977 it was invited to compete in the Hasidic Song Festival, an Israeli contest that ran from 1969 to 1984 and that was broadcast on national television.<ref name=mish/> Diaspora was the first yeshiva band to perform in the largely secular music event, and won first prize for its song \"''Hu Yiftach Libeinu''\" (He will open our hearts).<ref name=mish/> Interviews in the general media followed, increasing name recognition and visitors to the Saturday-night concerts.<ref name=mish/> The band was invited back for the 1978 Hasidic Song Festival, and won first prize for its song \"''Malchutcha''\" (Your sovereignty).<ref name=mish/>\n\nThe band embarked on its first North American concert tour in 1979, visiting 26 cities.<ref name=mish/> It went on to tour the U.S., Canada, Europe, and South Africa on five additional tours.<ref name=beatles/><ref name=shapiro>{{cite web |url=http://jewishtimes.com/17785/diaspora-yeshiva-band-reunites-after-almost-two-decades/#.U8W-W_mSzkU|last=Shapiro|first=Marc|title=Diaspora Yeshiva Band Reunites After Almost Two Decades|work=[[Baltimore Jewish Times]]|date=16 January 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> The band was highly popular on college campuses in the early to mid-1980s.{{sfn|Strom|2011|p=196}}<ref name=nymag>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GegCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA116&dq=diaspora+band |title=Music & Dance|journal=[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]|volume=15|issue=1|date=28 December 1981|accessdate=16 November 2014|page=116}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, [[Lynyrd Skynyrd]] drummer [[Artimus Pyle]] came to study in the Diaspora Yeshiva for several years.<ref name=arutz/> He played with the band and bequeathed his drum set to the yeshiva.<ref name=arutz>{{cite web |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/181355#.VFLBH_mUeHg|title=The Lynyrd Skynyrd Connection to Mount Zion & King David's Tomb|first=Ben|last=Bresky|work=[[Arutz Sheva|Israel National News]]|date=3 June 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=harris/> In 1987 the Diaspora Yeshiva Band performed and was interviewed on [[MTV]]'s Musical Passport series, ''Rock Israel'', as part of the coverage of the visit of [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers]] to Israel and Egypt.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?id=131506273571990&story_fbid=728705840518694|title=Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers Rock Israel 1987 (video)|publisher=Diaspora Yeshiva Band |accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=exponent/> Band leader Avraham Rosenblum was filmed accompanying [[Tom Petty]], [[Benmont Tench]], and [[Roger McGuinn]] at the [[Western Wall]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gruntig.net/2012/07/avraham-rosenblum-with-non-jewish-rock.html |title= Avraham Rosenblum with non-Jewish rock stars (video)|date=25 July 2012|accessdate=16 November 2014|publisher=gruntig.net}}</ref>\n\nThe Diaspora Yeshiva Band released a total of six albums.<ref name=mish/><ref name=sun/> It disbanded in 1983<ref name=bio/><ref name=sun/> as its members began pursuing both solo careers and careers in Torah learning and [[Orthodox Jewish outreach|outreach]].<ref name=mish/>\n\n===Reunions===\nIn December 1992 the band reconvened for a month-long<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/diasporayeshivaband|title=Live at Carnegie Hall &ndash; The Reunion|publisher=Sameach Music|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> reunion tour beginning with a performance at [[Carnegie Hall]].<ref name=beatles/><ref name=back>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-107976992.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042710/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-107976992.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 March 2015|title=Back From Musical Diaspora|first=George|last=Robinson|work=[[The Jewish Week]]|date=11 March 2005|accessdate=16 November 2014}} {{subscription}}</ref> It reunited again in 1996 with a show at [[The Town Hall (New York City)|The Town Hall]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=exponent>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2379407.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042701/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2379407.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 March 2015 |title= It's the Rockin' Rabbi: Avraham Rosenblum attuned to power of true music|first=Michael|last=Elkin|work=[[The Jewish Exponent]]|date=15 December 1995|accessdate=16 November 2014}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Rosenblum, Simcha Abramson, Gedaliah Goldstein, Ruby Harris, and Menachem Herman performed at the [[Hebrew Academy for Special Children#A Time for Music|HASC]] 27 concert at Lincoln Center.<ref name=mish>Besser, Yisroel. \"We All Get Another Chance\". ''[[Mishpacha]]'', March 12, 2014, pp. 48-58.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltimorejewishlife.com/news/news-detail.php?SECTION_ID=1&ARTICLE_ID=45577|title=HASC Donor Pays $300,000 for an Avraham Rosenblum Song|date=16 January 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=Baltimore Jewish Life|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129021253/http://baltimorejewishlife.com/news/news-detail.php?SECTION_ID=1&ARTICLE_ID=45577|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> That same year, the group held another reunion concert at [[Congregation Shomrei Emunah]] in Baltimore, where Rosenblum is a member.<ref name=shapiro/>\n\n===Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora===\nIn 1998 band leader Avraham Rosenblum and his son, drummer Moe Rosenblum, revived the band under the name '''Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora''' and produced the album ''Jerusalem is Calling''.<ref name=back/><ref name=av>{{cite web |url=http://rockinrabbi.com/bio.php|title=Biography/Information|publisher=Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora|year=2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-94584732.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042714/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-94584732.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= 29 March 2015|title=Like Father, Like Son|first=Steve|last=Lipman|date=26 March 2004|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=The Jewish Week}} {{subscription}}</ref> The pair went on to produce ''The Diaspora Collection'' (2000), a digitally-remastered double-CD of Diaspora Yeshiva Band hits, and ''Kedem'' (2003), an album featuring solo material by Avraham Rosenblum.<ref name=back/><ref name=av/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-93680585.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042716/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-93680585.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 March 2015|title=Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora: Kedem|first=Ben|last=Jacobson|date=21 April 2004|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=The Jerusalem Post}} {{subscription}}></ref>\n\n==Music style==\n{{Quote box\n |width=300px\n |align=right\n |quoted=true\n |bgcolor=#c6dbf7 \n |salign=right\n |quote=\"They started putting their music talents together in a religious way ... You remember that song \"[[Joy to the World (Three Dog Night song)|Jeremiah Was a Bullfrog]]\"? Well, it was the same sound, but they were singing about how wonderful God is\". |source=Shelley Lang, promoter<ref name=sun/>\n}}\nThe band members viewed their music as a means of expressing their newfound connection to God, the Jewish people, and the Land of Israel in a medium that they were familiar with.<ref name=bio/><ref name=report>{{cite web |url=http://jewishmusicreport.com/2009/11/17/ethnomusicology-the-americanization-of-niggunim/|title=Ethnomusicology &ndash; The Americanization of Niggunim|date=17 November 2009|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=Jewish Music Report}}</ref> Their arrangements reflected the musical trends of secular American culture in the late 1960s and early 1970s.<ref name=mish/> The band's repertoire included [[Rock music|rock]], [[soft rock]], [[acid rock]], [[Country music|country]], [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]], [[blues]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[jazz]], [[klezmer]], and [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]] ballads.<ref name=beatles>{{cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-12-18/features/9204250297_1_king-david-rock-diaspora-yeshiva-band |title='Jewish Beatles'|first=Anthony |last=DeBartolo|date=18 December 1992|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref><ref name=nymag/>{{sfn|Ledgin|2004|p=52}}<ref>Cohen, Judah M. (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZnbXkSNJa1gC&pg=PA107 \"Exploring the Postmodern Landscape of Jewish Music\u201d], in '' 'You Should See Yourself': Jewish Identity in Postmodern American Culture\", Vincent Brock, ed. Rutgers University Press, {{ISBN|081353996X}}, p. 107.</ref>{{sfn|Heilman|1986|pp=183-184}} [[Yale Strom|Strom]] describes their music as blending \"a San Francisco rock 'n' roll sound with Israeli, Middle Eastern, and Hasidic music\".{{sfn|Strom|2011|p=196}}\n\nInstrumentation included [[electric guitar]], [[rhythm guitar]], [[bass guitar]], [[saxophone]], [[fiddle]], [[banjo]], and [[Drum kit|drums]].<ref name=mish/><ref name=sun/> The band was noted for its guitar harmonies<ref name=shapiro/> and \"virtuoso\" instrument playing.<ref name=shapiro/><ref name=klig/>\n\nThe lyrics, in contrast, expressed Jewish values. Lyrics were both original and drawn from the [[Torah]] and [[Book of Psalms]].<ref name=beatles/><ref name=sun>{{cite web |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1992-12-26/news/9203080643_1_band-members-rock-band-reunion-tour|title=Jewish Band Takes Rock To Higher Level|first=Kirstin Norling|last=Walker|date=26 December 1992|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]}}</ref> The band sang in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]], and [[English language|English]].{{sfn|Tilbury|1989|p=193}} Their on-stage presence also belied the traditional rock band image: they sported full beards, ''[[payot]]'', and ''[[tzitzit]]'',{{sfn|Heilman|1986|pp=183-184}} and dressed in the dark-colored attire typical of yeshiva students.<ref name=bio/><ref name=mish/>\n\n==Influence==\nThe Diaspora Yeshiva Band was considered an influential group in the history of contemporary Jewish religious music.<ref name=klig>{{cite journal |url=http://www.bjpa.org/Publications/details.cfm?PublicationID=14722 |title=Contemporary Jewish Music in America|first=Mark|last=Kligman|year=2001|journal=American Jewish Yearbook|publisher=[[American Jewish Committee]]|page=109}}</ref> Bands that name them as an inspiration include [[Blue Fringe]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-87056408.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042706/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-87056408.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 March 2015|title=New Jewish Band Makes Waves|first=Michael|last=Freund|date=11 November 2003|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=The Jerusalem Post}} {{subscription}}</ref> [[8th Day (Jewish band)|8th Day]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kessertorah.nsw.edu.au/events/8thday.html|title=About 8th Day|publisher=Kesser Torah College|year=2012|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> and [[Shlock Rock]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.jta.org/2012/01/25/arts-entertainment/25-years-later-shlock-rock-is-still-rockin|title=25 years later, Shlock Rock is still rockin'|first=Michael|last=Feldstein|date=25 January 2012|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency|JTA]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-92661010.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042704/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-92661010.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= 29 March 2015|title=Solomon Keeps On Schlockin'|first=Ben|last=Jacobson|date=25 March 2004|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=The Jerusalem Post}} {{subscription}}</ref> Besides Rosenblum, other original band members who pursued solo careers include Ruby Harris, founder of the Ruby Harris Electric Violin Blues Band in Chicago,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.juf.org/interactive/default.aspx?id=75039 |title= AUDIO: Paul Wieder interviews Ruby Harris |date=3 February 2009|accessdate=16 November 2014|publisher=[[Jewish United Fund]]}}</ref> [[Adam Wexler]], co-founder of [[Reva L'Sheva]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.jpost.com/Arts-and-Culture/Music/Reva-LShevas-seven-year-itch-336804|title=Reva L'Sheva's seven-year itch|first=David|last=Brinn|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=1 January 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> and Rabbi Moshe Shur, founder of the Moshe Shur Band and Moshe Shur and Sons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qchron.com/editions/north/rabbi-moshe-shur-a-renaissance-man/article_f2b55433-69ac-55de-9d60-8dee638f1fb8.html|title=Rabbi Moshe Shur: A renaissance man|first=Jason|last=Cohen|date=3 March 2011|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[Queens Chronicle]]}}</ref> Sons of original band member [[Ben Zion Solomon]] include [[Noah Solomon]] of [[Soulfarm]], [[Yehuda Solomon]] of [[Moshav (band)|Moshav Band]], and Nachman Solomon of [[Hamakor (band)|Hamakor]].<ref name=forward/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117460491.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042708/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117460491.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= 29 March 2015|title=Two Start-Up Bands Step Up|first=Ben |last=Jacobson|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=13 January 2006|accessdate=16 November 2014}} {{subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/music/article/the_source_of_haumlmakor_its_all_in_the_family_20080625 |title= The source of h\u00e4MAKOR &ndash; It's all in the family|first=Paula|last=Roth|date=26 June 2008|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nThe six founding members of the Diaspora Yeshiva Band were:<ref name=mish/><ref name=harris>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishmag.com/114mag/band/band.htm|title=The Band That Changed Jewish Music|first=Ruby|last=Harris|date=June 2007|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=The Jewish Magazine}}</ref> \n* Avraham Rosenblum \u2013 guitar\n* [[Ben Zion Solomon]] \u2013 fiddle, banjo\n* Simcha Abramson \u2013 saxophone, clarinet\n* Ruby Harris \u2013 violin, mandolin, guitar, harmonica\n* [[Adam Wexler]] \u2013 bass\n* Gedalia Goldstein \u2013 drums\n\nStudent-musicians who played with the band at different times between 1973 and 1986 include: Beryl and Ted Glaser, Shimon Green, Isser Blum, Amram Hakohen, Menachem Herman, Yochanan Lederman, Tzvi Miller, Yosil Rosenzweig, [[Chaim-Dovid Saracik]], and Rabbi Moshe Shur.<ref name=harris/>\n\n==Discography==\n===Diaspora Yeshiva Band===\n* ''The Diaspora Yeshiva Band'' (1976)\n* ''Melave Malka with the Diaspora Yeshiva Band'' (1977)\n* ''At the Gate of Return'' (1978)\n* ''Live From King David's Tomb'' (1980)\n* ''Land of Our Fathers'' (1981)\n* ''Diaspora Live on Mt. Zion'' (1982)\n* ''Live at Carnegie Hall'' (1992)\n* ''The Diaspora Collection'' (2000)\n\n===Avraham Rosenblum & Diaspora===\n* ''Jerusalem is Calling'' (1998)\n* ''Kedem'' (2003)\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=AZttAAAAMAAJ&q=diaspora+yeshiva+band|title=A Walker in Jerusalem|first=Samuel C.|last=Heilman|authorlink=Samuel Heilman|publisher=Summit Books|year=1986|isbn= 0671544330}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0NrIPT7KWTYC&pg=PT325 |title=Contemporary American Judaism: Transformation and renewal|first=Dana Evan|last=Kaplan|year=2013|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=0231510411}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZbDQpgZILuwC&pg=PA330 |title=Judaism and Crisis: Crisis as a catalyst in Jewish cultural history|first1=Armin |last1=Lange|first2=K. F. |last2=Diethard Romheld|first3=Matthias|last3=Weigol|year=2011|publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht|isbn=3525542089}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7kgBY8tV6zYC&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52|title=Homegrown Music: Discovering Bluegrass|last=Ledgin|first=Stephanie P. |year=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=0275981150}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kAxLAn6sOb4C&pg=PA129 |title= Popular Music and National Culture in Israel|first1= Motti |last1=Regev|first2=Edwin|last2=Seroussi|year=2004|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=0520236548}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url= https://books.google.com/books?ei=7mFNVIK-M4TPaM2ugYgC&id=eJJtAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=band+concert |last=Selavan|first=Barnea Levi|title=Tzaddik's Guide to Jerusalem's Old City|year=1993|publisher=B. L. Selavan}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fxgZfheWUrIC&pg=PA92|title=Kids Love Israel \u2013 Israel Loves Kids: A travel guide for families|first=Barbara|last=Sofer|year=1995|publisher=Kar-Ben Publishing|isbn=0929371895}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i7w0s2ddCMEC&pg=PA196 |title=The Book of Klezmer: The history, the music, the folklore|first=Yale|last=Strom|authorlink=Yale Strom|year=2011|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=1613740638|edition=Reprint}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LSO7AAAAIAAJ&q=diaspora+yeshiva+band|title=Israel, a travel survival kit|first=Neil|last=Tilbury|year=1989|publisher=[[Lonely Planet]]|isbn= 0864420153}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.diasporaband.com/video/ Diaspora Band Video Channel]\n*[http://www.jewishpress.com/tv/video-picks/the-diaspora-yeshiva-band-1979/2014/04/25/ \"The Diaspora Yeshiva Band (1979)\"] (video)\n*[http://www.israelnationalnews.com/Radio/News.aspx/3206#.VF_oNPmUewR \u201cAudio: Avraham Rosenblum - Diaspora Yeshiva Band & Beyond\u201d] 2011 live performance and interview\n\n{{Contemporary Jewish religious music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diaspora Yeshiva Band}}\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Israeli rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1975]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:Jewish rock groups]]\n[[Category:Jewish folk rock groups]]\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diaspora_Yeshiva_Band"}
{"title_page": "Money in the Bank (2020)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 WWE pay-per-view and WWE Network event}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n<!--{{current sport|sport=pro wrestling|event=professional wrestling PPV}}-->\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = Money in the Bank (2020)\n|image      = MITB2020poster.jpeg\n|caption    = Promotional poster featuring various [[List of WWE personnel|WWE wrestlers]]\n|tagline    = Climb the Corporate Ladder<ref name=MITBlocation>{{cite web|last=Tedesco|first=Mike|title=Money in the Bank Ladder Matches to take place at WWE Headquarters in Stamford|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/154148-money-in-the-bank-ladder-matches-to-take-place-at-wwe-headquarters-in-stamford/|work=WrestleView|date=April 17, 2020|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n|promotion  = [[WWE]]\n|brand      = [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]]<br>[[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]]\n|date       = May 10, 2020\n|date_aired = \n|attendance = 0{{efn|name=Attendance|The event will be held without a live audience due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]].}}\n|venue      = [[Titan Towers|WWE Global Headquarters]]{{efn|The event's Money in the Bank ladder matches will take place at WWE's [[Titan Towers|global headquarters]] in [[Stamford, Connecticut]], while the venue of the remaining matches has not been announced.}}\n|city       = [[Stamford, Connecticut]]\n|wwenlast   = [[WrestleMania 36]]\n|wwennext   = \n|event      = [[WWE Money in the Bank|Money in the Bank]]\n|lastevent2 = [[Money in the Bank (2019)|2019]]\n|nextevent2 = \n}}\n'''Money in the Bank''' is an upcoming [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) and [[WWE Network]] [[List of WWE pay-per-view and WWE Network events|event]], produced by [[WWE]] for their [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]] and [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]] [[WWE brand extension|brand divisions]]. It is scheduled to take place on May 10, 2020. It will be the eleventh event under the [[WWE Money in the Bank|Money in the Bank]] chronology.\n\nThe event was originally scheduled to take place at the [[Royal Farms Arena]] in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], but the venue canceled all shows that were to be held in May [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports|due to the]] [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. WWE announced that the show's [[Money in the Bank ladder match|eponymous ladder matches]] would take place at its \"[[Titan Towers]]\" global headquarters building in [[Stamford, Connecticut]] with a new \"Corporate Ladder\" gimmick culminating on the facility's chatt. WWE has not yet announced where the card's remaining matches will originate.\n\n== Production ==\n=== Background ===\n[[WWE Money in the Bank|Money in the Bank]] (MITB) is an annual [[gimmick]] pay-per-view produced by WWE since 2010 and generally held between May and July. The concept of the show comes from WWE's established [[Money in the Bank ladder match]], in which multiple wrestlers use [[Ladder match|ladders]] to retrieve a briefcase hanging above the ring. The briefcase contains a contract that guarantees the winner a match for a world championship of their choosing at any time within the next year. Since the [[Money in the Bank (2018)|2018 event]], both the men's and women's matches featured eight wrestlers, evenly divided between the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]] and [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]] [[WWE brand extension|brands]]. For 2020, it was reduced to six wrestlers divided between the brands. Male wrestlers compete for a contract to grant them a match for either Raw's [[WWE Championship]] or SmackDown's [[WWE Universal Championship|Universal Championship]], while female wrestlers compete for a [[Raw Women's Championship]] or [[SmackDown Women's Championship]] match contract. 2020 will be the eleventh event in the Money in the Bank chronology.<ref name=\"2020event\"/>\n\n====Impact of the coronavirus pandemic====\nThe event was originally announced with [[Baltimore]]'s [[Royal Farms Arena]] as host.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lambert|first=Jeremy|title=WWE Money In The Bank 2020 Scheduled For May 10 In Baltimore, MD|url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/wwe-money-bank-2020-scheduled-may-10-baltimore-md|work=Fightful|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"2020event\">{{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Mike|title=WWE MONEY IN THE BANK 2020 DETAILS|url=https://pwinsider.com/article/134349/wwe-money-in-the-bank-2020-details.html?p=1|work=PWInsider|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> However, [[Maryland]] issued a [[stay at home order]] on March 30, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Maryland to Enact Stay-at-Home Order Monday as Coronavirus Cases Top 1,400|last=Barnes|first=Sophia|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/maryland-governor-larry-hogan-latest-monday-march-30-coronavirus-outbreak-covid-19-stay-at-home-order/2258161/|work=NBC4 Washington|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Subsequently on April 9, the host venue cancelled the event due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], and began issuing refunds. WWE initially did not announce whether the event will still go on from a different location (such as the [[WWE Performance Center]] in [[Orlando]] where most WWE shows have been held since mid-March),<ref>{{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Mike|title=WWE MONEY IN THE BANK WILL NOT TAKE PLACE IN BALTIMORE, ROYAL FARMS ARENA ANNOUNCES CANCELLATION|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/135465/wwe-money-in-the-bank-will-not-take-place-in-baltimore-royal-farms-arena-announces-cancellation.html?p=1|work=PWInsider|date=April 9, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wilen|first=Jerome|title=WWE Money in the Bank pay-per view canceled due to COVID-19 outbreak|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/153495-wwe-money-in-the-bank-pay-per-view-canceled-covid-19/|work=WrestleView|date=April 9, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> though the company did air an advertisement promoting Money in the Bank during the second half of [[WrestleMania 36]].<ref name=\"WM36Part2\">{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=WrestleMania 36 results: Powell\u2019s live review of Night Two featuring Brock Lesnar vs. Drew McIntyre for the WWE Championship, John Cena vs. \u201cThe Fiend\u201d Bray Wyatt in a Firefly Funhouse match, Edge vs. Randy Orton in a Last Man Standing match, Rhea Ripley vs. Charlotte Flair for the NXT Women\u2019s Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/05/wrestlemania-36-results-powells-live-review-of-night-two-featuring-brock-lesnar-vs-drew-mcintyre-for-the-wwe-championship-john-cena-vs-the-fiend-bray-wyatt-in-a-firefly-funhouse-match/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe pandemic brought about a modification to the Money in the Bank ladder matches. During the April 17 episode of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]]'', it was announced that the two Money in the Bank ladder matches would take place at WWE's [[Titan Towers|global headquarters]] in [[Stamford, Connecticut]]. A new \"[[Career ladder|Corporate Ladder]]\" gimmick was also added to the matches, in which the participants must travel from the ground floor of the building to the roof in order to locate the briefcase, which itself is suspended above a ring on the roof.<ref name=MITBlocation/><ref>{{cite web|title=WWE Superstars will climb the corporate ladder at WWE Money In The Bank|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/moneyinthebank/2020/article/money-in-the-bank-climb-the-corporate-ladder|work=WWE|date=April 17, 2020|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Storylines===\nThe show will include matches that result from scripted storylines, where wrestlers portray [[Face (professional wrestling)|heroes]], [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villains]], or [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Tweener|less distinguishable characters]] in scripted events that build tension and culminate in a wrestling match or series of matches. Results are predetermined by WWE's writers on the Raw and SmackDown brands,<ref name=\"HSW\">{{cite web|title=How Pro Wrestling Works|url=http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/pro-wrestling.htm|last=Grabianowski|first=Ed|work=HowStuffWorks|publisher=[[Discovery Communications]]|access-date=March 5, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6LDla2zy5?url=http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/pro-wrestling.htm|archive-date=November 18, 2013|df=}}</ref><ref name=WWEnt>{{cite web|title=Live & Televised Entertainment|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/company/events.jsp|publisher=WWE|access-date=March 21, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5esskNFVE?url=http://corporate.wwe.com/company/events.jsp|archive-date=February 26, 2009|df=}}</ref> while storylines are produced on WWE's weekly television shows, ''[[Monday Night Raw]]'' and ''[[Friday Night SmackDown]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/wwe-smackdown-live-usa-1201782569/|title=WWE's 'Smackdown' Will Move To Live Broadcast On USA (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|date=May 25, 2016|website=Variety|language=en-US|access-date=May 25, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526113045/http://variety.com/2016/tv/news/wwe-smackdown-live-usa-1201782569/|archive-date=May 26, 2016|df=}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Super ShowDown (2020)|Super ShowDown]], [[\"The Fiend\" Bray Wyatt]] lost the [[WWE Universal Championship|Universal Championship]] to [[Bill Goldberg|Goldberg]],<ref name=\"SuperShowDown2020\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=WWE Super ShowDown results: Powell's live review of \"The Fiend\" Bray Wyatt vs. Goldberg for the WWE Universal Championship, Brock Lesnar vs. Ricochet for the WWE Championship, Big E and Kofi Kingston vs. The Miz and John Morrison for the Smackdown Tag Titles|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/02/27/wwe-super-showdown-results-powells-live-review-of-the-fiend-bray-wyatt-vs-goldberg-for-the-wwe-universal-championship-brock-lesnar-vs-ricochet-for-the-wwe-championship-big-e-and-kofi-kingst/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref> who in turn lost the title to [[Braun Strowman]] during [[WrestleMania 36]] Part 1.<ref name=\"WM36Part1\">{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=WrestleMania 36 results: Powell's live review of night one featuring Goldberg vs. Braun Strowman for the WWE Universal Championship, Undertaker vs. AJ Styles in a Boneyard match, Becky Lynch vs. Shayna Baszler for the Raw Women's Championship, Seth Rollins vs. Kevin Owens|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/04/wrestlemania-36-results-powells-live-review-of-night-one-featuring-goldberg-vs-braun-strowman-for-the-wwe-universal-championship-undertaker-vs-aj-styles-in-a-boneyard-match-becky-lynch-vs-shay/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|date=April 4, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> On the following episode of ''SmackDown'', Wyatt interrupted Strowman after his match and reminded Strowman that it was he who brought him to the WWE with his old [[The Wyatt Family|Wyatt Family]] stable. Wyatt then stated he wanted his title back and Strowman accepted the challenge, which was scheduled for Money in the Bank, though against Wyatt's normal self instead of The Fiend.<ref name=\"SmackDown04102020\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/10/4-10-wwe-friday-night-smackdown-results-powells-review-of-braun-strowmans-first-appearance-as-wwe-universal-champion-alexa-bliss-and-nikki-cross-vs-the-kabuki-warriors-for-the-wwe-womens-tag/|title=4/10 WWE Friday Night Smackdown results: Powell\u2019s review of Braun Strowman\u2019s first appearance as WWE Universal Champion, Alexa Bliss and Nikki Cross vs. The Kabuki Warriors for the WWE Women\u2019s Tag Titles, WrestleMania 36 fallout|date=April 10, 2020|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQualifying matches for the women's Money in the Bank ladder match began on the April 13 episode of ''Raw''. [[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]], [[Shayna Baszler]], and [[Nia Jax]] qualified for the match by defeating [[Ruby Riott]], [[Sarah Logan]], and [[Kairi Sane]], respectively.<ref name=\"Raw04132020\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=4/13 WWE Raw Results: Powell\u2019s live review of Drew McIntyre and Becky Lynch appearances, Money in the Bank qualifying matches featuring Asuka vs. Ruby Riott, Kairi Sane vs. Nia Jax, and Sarah Logan vs. Shayna Baszler|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/13/4-13-wwe-raw-results-powells-live-review-of-drew-mcintyre-and-becky-lynch-appearances-money-in-the-bank-qualifying-matches-featuring-asuka-vs-ruby-riott-kairi-sane-vs-nia-jax-and-sarah-logan-v/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> On the April 17 episode of ''SmackDown'', [[Dana Brooke]] defeated [[Naomi (wrestler)|Naomi]] to qualify for the match.<ref name=\"SmackDown04172020\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=4/17 WWE Friday Night Smackdown results: Powell\u2019s review of The Miz vs. Jey Uso vs. Big E in a Triple Threat for the Smackdown Tag Titles, Daniel Bryan vs. Cesaro and Naomi vs. Dana Brooke in Money in the Bank qualifiers, Sasha Banks vs. Tamina|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/17/4-17-wwe-friday-night-smackdown-results-powells-review-of-the-miz-vs-jey-uso-vs-big-e-in-a-triple-threat-for-the-smackdown-tag-titles-daniel-bryan-vs-cesaro-and-naomi-vs-dana-brooke-in-money-i/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=April 17, 2020|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQualifying matches for the men's Money in the Bank ladder match began on the April 17 episode of ''SmackDown''. [[Daniel Bryan]] defeated [[Cesaro (wrestler)|Cesaro]] to qualify for the match.<ref name=\"SmackDown04172020\"/>\n\nDuring WrestleMania 36 Part 2, [[Tamina Snuka|Tamina]] was eliminated first in the [[fatal five-way elimination match]] for the [[SmackDown Women's Championship]] due to all of the other competitors piling on top of her for the pin; [[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]] subsequently retained the title.<ref name=\"WM36Part2\">{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=WrestleMania 36 results: Powell\u2019s live review of Night Two featuring Brock Lesnar vs. Drew McIntyre for the WWE Championship, John Cena vs. \u201cThe Fiend\u201d Bray Wyatt in a Firefly Funhouse match, Edge vs. Randy Orton in a Last Man Standing match, Rhea Ripley vs. Charlotte Flair for the NXT Women\u2019s Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/05/wrestlemania-36-results-powells-live-review-of-night-two-featuring-brock-lesnar-vs-drew-mcintyre-for-the-wwe-championship-john-cena-vs-the-fiend-bray-wyatt-in-a-firefly-funhouse-match/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> On the following ''SmackDown'', Tamina pointed out the fact that Bayley nor any other competitor in that match actually beat her and challenged Bayley to a [[singles match]] for the championship. Bayley agreed if Tamina could defeat her friend [[Sasha Banks]],<ref name=\"SmackDown04102020\"/> which she did the following week to earn the title match at Money in the Bank.<ref name=\"SmackDown04172020\"/>\n\n== Matches ==\n<!-- Please do not add any matches you may have heard on the internet or during taping, without a reliable source, such as the company's official website or other reliable websites. -->\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|times  = \n|future = yes\n|match1 = [[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]] vs. [[Shayna Baszler]] vs. [[Nia Jax]] vs. [[Dana Brooke]] vs. [[Lacey Evans]] or [[Sasha Banks]] vs. [[TBD]]\n|stip1  = [[Money in the Bank ladder match]] for a [[Professional wrestling championship#Gender championships|women's championship]] match contract<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's Money in the Bank Ladder Match|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/moneyinthebank/2020/womens-money-in-the-bank-ladder-match|work=WWE|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> \n|time1  = \n|match2 = [[Daniel Bryan]